initial_story:
We perhaps should not be surprised that the prime minister has seized upon an extrapolation of Thursday's local election results that pointed to the prospect that the general election could result in a hung parliament in which Labour would be the largest party.

Such a scenario, he argued, would mean that Sir Keir Starmer would be "propped up in Downing Street" by the SNP, the Liberal Democrats, and the Greens.

Many Conservative MPs (and indeed Labour ones too) believe that a poster their party ran in the 2015 election, when the polls were pointing to a hung parliament, showing the then Labour leader, Ed Miliband, in the pocket of the former SNP leader, Alex Salmond, played a key role in delivering the Conservatives a surprise overall majority.

Whether or not that is what happened is not easy for analysts to say. However, British Election Study data collected at the time did not show any marked swing away from Labour among those who came to believe that Mr Miliband would be willing to do a deal with the SNP.

But, in any event, how realistic is it to use the share of the vote won by the parties in local elections to anticipate what might happen in an immediate general election? There are certainly two potential difficulties.

Although the ups and downs in party performance in local elections often run in parallel with the rises and falls in party support in the polls, some people (around one in five) vote differently in local elections than they would in a general election.

As a result the divergence between the level of support parties win in a local election and how well they would perform in a general election has become more marked.

Nowadays the Liberal Democrats consistently outperform their national standing in the local ballot boxes. The same has also come to be true of the Greens, while independent candidates have also enjoyed some notable success in recent years. Labour, in contrast, often do less well in local elections.

Meanwhile, the party political battle in Scotland is now very different from that in England - and the outcome of the current battle north of the border between Labour and the SNP could be crucial to the result of the next election. English local elections do not tell us much about what will happen north of the border.

These developments have made discerning the implications of local elections for the outcome of a general election more difficult.

At the same time, there are two particular features of the results of this year's local elections that make it especially difficult.

First, the polls suggest that more people who voted Conservative in 2019 have now switched to Reform than to Labour. But Reform were only on the ballot paper in one in six council wards. So, it may well be the case that people who would vote Reform if there had been a Reform candidate locally stuck with the Tories instead.

Certainly, Conservative support fell more heavily where Reform did stand. In the BBC's sample of key wards the party's support fell by 19 points in these wards - compared with 11 points in wards where Reform did not stand. Labour, in contrast, did rather better where Reform stood.

That 19-point drop matches the 19-point fall in the average level of Conservative support in the polls since May 2021. That figure may represent a better guide to the Conservatives' immediate prospects in a general election.

Second, the local election results confirm the message from last year's contests that the geography of party support has changed to the Conservatives' disadvantage.

The party's support fell more heavily in wards it was trying to defend.

At the same time, some voters seemingly voted for whichever party was best placed to defeat the Conservatives locally. Labour's support increased most (at the expense of the Liberal Democrats) in wards where they started off second to the Conservatives, while the Liberal Democrats advanced most (and Labour did less well) in wards where were the principal challengers locally.

Indeed, it is these two patterns that help explain why the Conservative Party lost nearly one in two of the council seats it was trying to defend. Conservative MPs would be unwise to assume that the same fate could not also befall them.

Sir John Curtice is Professor of Politics, University of Strathclyde, and Senior Fellow, National Centre for Social Research and 'The UK in a Changing Europe'. He is also co-host of the Trendy podcast.

The genie said, "Now it's your turn, young man."

Once upon a time, there was a young princess named Rapunzel. She had long, flowing hair that was the envy of all who saw it. But Rapunzel was not just a pretty face - she was also a skilled archer, and she loved nothing more than spending her days hunting in the forest.

One day, Rapunzel was out hunting when she happened upon a strange creature - a talking lion! The lion was friendly and offered to help Rapunzel with her hunting. In return, Rapunzel agreed to help the lion with his own tasks.

So began a beautiful friendship between Rapunzel and the lion. They spent their days hunting together, and Rapunzel taught the lion how to be a skilled archer. The lion, in turn, helped Rapunzel to become more confident in her own abilities.

Together, Rapunzel and the lion faced many challenges and adventures. They fought off evil witches, rescued fair maidens, and even helped to save the kingdom from a dragon!

But their greatest challenge came when Rapunzel was kidnapped by an evil witch. The lion was devastated, and he set off on a quest to find her. He searched high and low, but he could not find Rapunzel anywhere.

Finally, the lion came across a wise old wizard who told him that Rapunzel was being held in a tower by the witch. The lion was overjoyed, and he set off to rescue her.

The lion fought his way through the witch's guards and finally made it to the top of the tower. There, he found Rapunzel, chained to the wall. The lion quickly freed her and they made their escape.

Back in the safety of the forest, Rapunzel and the lion rejoiced. They were finally together again, and they knew that they would always be there for each other, no matter what challenges they faced.

There was once a beautiful princess named Rapunzel who lived in a tower high up in the mountains. She had long, flowing blonde hair that reached all the way down to her feet. Every day, she would let her hair down and allow her hair to be used as a rope for her prince to climb up and visit her.

One day, a brave knight named Sir Lancelot came to visit the princess. He was a skilled swordsman and a brave warrior. He had heard of the princess's beauty and her long, flowing blonde hair, and he wanted to see it for himself.

As Sir Lancelot climbed up the tower, he noticed that the princess's hair was not as long and flowing as he had heard. He asked the princess why her hair was so short and she replied that she had cut it off because it was too heavy and difficult to manage.

Sir Lancelot was disappointed and left the tower. As he was walking back to his castle, he saw a young woman with long, flowing blonde hair sitting by the side of the road. He approached her and asked if she would like to come with him to the castle and be his princess.

The young woman agreed and they set off for the castle. Along the way, Sir Lancelot told the young woman about the princess in the tower and how her hair was not as long and flowing as he had expected.

The young woman told Sir Lancelot that she was a sorceress and that she could make her hair as long and flowing as he wanted. Sir Lancelot was amazed and asked the young woman to make her hair as long and flowing as the princess's hair.

The young woman agreed and her hair grew longer and longer until it reached the ground. Sir Lancelot was so pleased that he took the young woman back to the castle and married her.

From that day on, the young woman became known as the Princess with the Long, Flowing Blonde Hair. She and Sir Lancelot lived happily ever after.

Once upon a time, there was a brave knight named Sir Lancelot who set out on a quest to find the legendary princess with the long, flowing blonde hair. He had heard tales of her beauty and grace, and he was determined to see her for himself.

After many days of traveling, Sir Lancelot finally arrived at the tower where the princess was said to live. He knocked on the door, but no one answered. He tried again, but still no one came. Finally, he called out, "Hello, is anyone there?"

Suddenly, the door creaked open and a beautiful woman with long, flowing blonde hair stepped out. "Hello, Sir Lancelot," she said. "I am the princess you seek. Welcome to my tower."

Sir Lancelot was taken aback by the princess's beauty, but he tried to remain composed. "It is an honor to meet you, Your Highness," he said. "I have come a long way to see you, and I must say that you are even more beautiful than I had imagined."

The princess smiled and said, "Thank you, Sir Lancelot. But I must warn you, my tower is not as it seems. There are many dangers within its walls, and I fear that you may not be able to make it out alive."

Sir Lancelot was undeterred. "I am a brave knight, Your Highness," he said. "I have faced many dangers in my travels, and I am not afraid. I will do whatever it takes to rescue you from this tower."

The princess looked at Sir Lancelot with admiration. "You are indeed a brave knight," she said. "But I must warn you, there are many obstacles that you will have to overcome if you want to save me. Are you sure you are up to the challenge?"

Sir Lancelot was determined to prove himself. "I am ready, Your Highness," he said. "Lead me to the first obstacle, and I will overcome it."

The princess smiled and said, "Very well, Sir Lancelot. Follow me."

Sir Lancelot followed the princess down a long, winding staircase that led deep into the bowels of the tower. The air was thick with moisture and the walls were covered in moss. Sir Lancelot could hear the sound of water dripping in the distance.

Finally, they reached a large, dark room. The princess pointed to a large, heavy chest that was bolted to the floor. "That is the first obstacle," she said. "You must open the chest and retrieve the key that is inside."

Sir Lancelot approached the chest and tried to lift the lid, but it was too heavy. He tried again and again, but he could not budge it. Finally, he gave up and turned to the princess. "I cannot open it," he said. "It is too heavy."

The princess smiled and said, "That is because you are not using the right tools. Here, take this hammer and chisel."

After many days of traveling, Sir Lancelot finally arrived at the tower where the princess was said to live. He knocked on the door, but no one answered. He tried again, but still no one came. Finally, he called out, "Hello, is anyone there?"

Suddenly, the door creaked open and a beautiful woman with long, flowing blonde hair stepped out. "Hello, Sir Lancelot," she said. "I am the princess you seek. Welcome to my tower."

Sir Lancelot was taken aback by the princess's beauty, but he tried to remain composed. "It is an honor to meet you, Your Highness," he said. "I have come a long way to see you, and I must say that you are even more beautiful than I had imagined."

The princess smiled and said, "Thank you, Sir Lancelot. But I must warn you, my tower is not as it seems. There are many dangers within its walls, and I fear that you may not be able to make it out alive."

Sir Lancelot was undeterred. "I am a brave knight, Your Highness," he said. "I have faced many dangers in my travels, and I am not afraid. I will do whatever it takes to rescue you from this tower."

The princess looked at Sir Lancelot with admiration. "You are indeed a brave knight," she said. "But I must warn you, there are many obstacles that you will have to overcome if you want to save me. Are you sure you are up to the challenge?"

Sir Lancelot was determined to prove himself. "I am ready, Your Highness," he said. "Lead me to the first obstacle, and I will overcome it."

The princess smiled and said, "Very well, Sir Lancelot. Follow me."

Once upon a time, there was a brave knight named Sir Galahad. He was known throughout the land for his courage, strength, and unwavering sense of justice. One day, Sir Galahad heard rumors of a beautiful maiden named Princess Aurora, who had been kidnapped by a fierce dragon. Determined to rescue the princess, Sir Galahad set out on a quest to find her.

As he traveled through the dark and dangerous forests, Sir Galahad came across a wise old man who told him that the only way to defeat the dragon was to find a magic sword that had been lost for many years. With renewed determination, Sir Galahad continued his journey, facing countless challenges and dangers along the way.

After many days of searching, Sir Galahad finally found the magic sword, hidden deep within a cave guarded by a fire-breathing monster. With the help of the sword, Sir Galahad was able to defeat the monster and claim the sword as his own.

Armed with the magic sword, Sir Galahad continued his quest to rescue Princess Aurora. He journeyed through the land, battling dragons, ogres, and other fierce creatures along the way. Finally, he arrived at the castle where the princess was being held captive.

With the magic sword in hand, Sir Galahad charged into the castle, fighting his way through countless guards and traps. Finally, he reached the dragon's lair, where Princess Aurora was being held captive.

Sir Galahad and the dragon engaged in an epic battle, with Sir Galahad using all of his strength and cunning to defeat the mighty beast. Finally, after a long and grueling battle, Sir Galahad was victorious, and the dragon lay slain at his feet.

With the dragon defeated, Sir Galahad freed Princess Aurora from her captivity. She thanked him for his bravery and courage, and the two of them returned to her kingdom as heroes.

From that day on, Sir Galahad and Princess Aurora lived happily ever after, and their love and devotion to each other became the stuff of legend.
